message.content: After $18$ years, at the age of $18$, the money will have had $18$ years to compound.  Therefore, the amount of money that Frederick will have is the principal, $P$, multiplied by one plus the interest rate, $r$, compounded $n$ times a year, raised to the power of $nt$, where $n$ is the number of times a year the interest is compounded, and $t$ is the number of years the money is invested for.  Hence, at the age of $18$, Frederick will have a total of $\$2000\left(1+\dfrac{.05}{1}\right)^{1\cdot 18}$ dollars.  Evaluating this expression, we find the amount to be $\$2000(1.05)^{18} = 2000(1.05^{10.5})\approx \boxed{\$5997.36}$.
